SKILL|p5js|"p5.js sketches: gen art, shaders, interactive, 3D."
STEP|1|Before writing a single line of code**, articulate the creative concept. What does this piece communicate? What makes the viewer stop scrolling? What separates this from a code tutorial example? The u
STEP|2|First-render excellence is non-negotiable.** The output must be visually striking on first load. If it looks like a p5.js tutorial exercise, a default configuration, or "AI-generated creative coding,"
STEP|3|Go beyond the reference vocabulary.** The noise functions, particle systems, color palettes, and shader effects in the references are a starting vocabulary. For every project, combine, layer, and inve
STEP|4|Be proactively creative.** If the user asks for "a particle system," deliver a particle system with emergent flocking behavior, trailing ghost echoes, palette-shifted depth fog, and a background noise
STEP|5|Dense, layered, considered.** Every frame should reward viewing. Never flat white backgrounds. Always compositional hierarchy. Always intentional color. Always micro-detail that only appears on close 
STEP|6|Cohesive aesthetic over feature count.** All elements must serve a unified visual language — shared color temperature, consistent stroke weight vocabulary, harmonious motion speeds. A sketch with ten 
STEP|7|p5.js 1.x** (1.11.3) is the default — stable, well-documented, broadest library compatibility. Use this unless a project requires 2.x features.
STEP|8|p5.js 2.x** (2.2+) adds: `async setup()` replacing `preload()`, OKLCH/OKLAB color modes, `splineVertex()`, shader `.modify()` API, variable fonts, `textToContours()`, pointer events. Required for p5.b
STEP|9|**CONCEPT** — Articulate the creative vision: mood, color world, motion vocabulary, what makes this unique
STEP|10|**DESIGN** — Choose mode, canvas size, interaction model, color system, export format. Map concept to technical decisions
STEP|11|**CODE** — Write single HTML file with inline p5.js. Structure: globals → `preload()` → `setup()` → `draw()` → helpers → classes → event handlers
STEP|12|**PREVIEW** — Open in browser, verify visual quality. Test at target resolution. Check performance
STEP|13|**EXPORT** — Capture output: `saveCanvas()` for PNG, `saveGif()` for GIF, `saveFrames()` + ffmpeg for MP4, Puppeteer for headless batch
STEP|14|**VERIFY** — Does the output match the concept? Is it visually striking at the intended display size? Would you frame it?
STEP|15|**Custom color palette** — never raw `fill(255, 0, 0)`. Always a designed palette with 3-7 colors
STEP|16|**Custom stroke weight vocabulary** — thin accents (0.5), medium structure (1-2), bold emphasis (3-5)
STEP|17|**Background treatment** — never plain `background(0)` or `background(255)`. Always textured, gradient, or layered
STEP|18|**Motion variety** — different speeds for different elements. Primary at 1x, secondary at 0.3x, ambient at 0.1x
STEP|19|**At least one invented element** — a custom particle behavior, a novel noise application, a unique interaction response
STEP|20|A custom color palette matching the mood (not a preset)
STEP|21|A novel noise field combination (e.g., curl noise + domain warp + feedback)
STEP|22|A unique particle behavior (custom forces, custom trails, custom spawning)
STEP|23|An interaction mechanic the user didn't request but that elevates the piece
STEP|24|A compositional technique that creates visual hierarchy
STEP|25|Good parameters** expose the algorithm's character:
STEP|26|**Quantities** — how many particles, branches, cells (controls density)
STEP|27|**Scales** — noise frequency, element size, spacing (controls texture)
STEP|28|**Rates** — speed, growth rate, decay (controls energy)
STEP|29|**Thresholds** — when does behavior change? (controls drama)
STEP|30|**Ratios** — proportions, balance between forces (controls harmony)
STEP|31|Bad parameters** are generic controls unrelated to the algorithm:
STEP|32|"color1", "color2", "size" — meaningless without context
STEP|33|Toggle switches for unrelated effects
STEP|34|Parameters that only change cosmetics, not behavior
STEP|35|**Mood / atmosphere**: What should the viewer feel? Contemplative? Energized? Unsettled? Playful?
STEP|36|**Visual story**: What happens over time (or on interaction)? Build? Decay? Transform? Oscillate?
STEP|37|**Color world**: Warm/cool? Monochrome? Complementary? What's the dominant hue? The accent?
STEP|38|**Shape language**: Organic curves? Sharp geometry? Dots? Lines? Mixed?
STEP|39|**Motion vocabulary**: Slow drift? Explosive burst? Breathing pulse? Mechanical precision?
STEP|40|**What makes THIS different**: What is the one thing that makes this sketch unique?
STEP|41|**Mode** — which of the 7 modes from the table above
STEP|42|**Canvas size** — landscape 1920x1080, portrait 1080x1920, square 1080x1080, or responsive `windowWidth/windowHeight`
STEP|43|**Renderer** — `P2D` (default) or `WEBGL` (for 3D, shaders, advanced blend modes)
STEP|44|**Frame rate** — 60fps (interactive), 30fps (ambient animation), or `noLoop()` (static generative)
STEP|45|**Export target** — browser display, PNG still, GIF loop, MP4 video, SVG vector
STEP|46|**Interaction model** — passive (no input), mouse-driven, keyboard-driven, audio-reactive, scroll-driven
STEP|47|**Viewer UI** — for interactive generative art, start from `templates/viewer.html` which provides seed navigation, parameter sliders, and download. For simple sketches or video export, use bare HTML
STEP|48|**Seeded randomness**: Always `randomSeed()` + `noiseSeed()` for reproducibility
STEP|49|**Color mode**: Use `colorMode(HSB, 360, 100, 100, 100)` for intuitive color control
STEP|50|**State separation**: CONFIG for parameters, PALETTE for colors, globals for mutable state
STEP|51|**Class-based entities**: Particles, agents, shapes as classes with `update()` + `display()` methods
STEP|52|**Offscreen buffers**: `createGraphics()` for layered composition, trails, masks
STEP|53|Open HTML file directly in browser — no server needed for basic sketches
STEP|54|For `loadImage()`/`loadFont()` from local files: use `scripts/serve.sh` or `python3 -m http.server`
STEP|55|Chrome DevTools Performance tab to verify 60fps
STEP|56|Test at target export resolution, not just the window size
STEP|57|Adjust parameters until the visual matches the concept from Step 1
STEP|58|**Does it match the vision?** Compare output to the creative concept. If it looks generic, go back to Step 1
STEP|59|**Resolution check**: Is it sharp at the target display size? No aliasing artifacts?
STEP|60|**Performance check**: Does it hold 60fps in browser? (30fps minimum for animations)
STEP|61|**Color check**: Do the colors work together? Test on both light and dark monitors
STEP|62|**Edge cases**: What happens at canvas edges? On resize? After running for 10 minutes?
STEP|63|`createCanvas(w, h, WEBGL)` — origin is center, not top-left
STEP|64|Y-axis is inverted (positive Y goes up in WEBGL, down in P2D)
STEP|65|`translate(-width/2, -height/2)` to get P2D-like coordinates
STEP|66|`push()`/`pop()` around every transform — matrix stack overflows silently
STEP|67|`texture()` before `rect()`/`plane()` — not after
STEP|68|Custom shaders: `createShader(vert, frag)` — test on multiple browsers
STEP|69|**Write the HTML file** — single self-contained file, all code inline
STEP|70|**Open in browser** — `open sketch.html` (macOS) or `xdg-open sketch.html` (Linux)
STEP|71|**Local assets** (fonts, images) require a server: `python3 -m http.server 8080` in the project directory, then open `http://localhost:8080/sketch.html`
STEP|72|**Export PNG/GIF** — add `keyPressed()` shortcuts as shown above, tell the user which key to press
STEP|73|**Headless export** — `node scripts/export-frames.js sketch.html --frames 300` for automated frame capture (sketch must use `noLoop()` + `_p5Ready`)
STEP|74|**MP4 rendering** — `bash scripts/render.sh sketch.html output.mp4 --duration 30`
STEP|75|**Iterative refinement** — edit the HTML file, user refreshes browser to see changes
STEP|76|**Load references on demand** — use `skill_view(name="p5js", file_path="references/...")` to load specific reference files as needed during implementation
STEP|77|**Conceptual Blending** — when the user names two things to combine or wants hybrid aesthetics
STEP|78|**SCAMPER** — when the user wants a twist on a known generative art pattern
STEP|79|**Distance Association** — when the user gives a single concept and wants exploration ("make something about time")
STEP|80|Name two distinct visual systems (e.g., particle physics + handwriting)
STEP|81|Map correspondences (particles = ink drops, forces = pen pressure, fields = letterforms)
STEP|82|Blend selectively — keep mappings that produce interesting emergent visuals
STEP|83|Code the blend as a unified system, not two systems side-by-side
STEP|84|**Substitute**: replace circles with text characters, lines with gradients
STEP|85|**Combine**: merge two patterns (flow field + voronoi)
STEP|86|**Adapt**: apply a 2D pattern to a 3D projection
STEP|87|**Modify**: exaggerate scale, warp the coordinate space
STEP|88|**Purpose**: use a physics sim for typography, a sorting algorithm for color
STEP|89|**Eliminate**: remove the grid, remove color, remove symmetry
STEP|90|**Reverse**: run the simulation backward, invert the parameter space
STEP|91|Anchor on the user's concept (e.g., "loneliness")
STEP|92|Generate associations at three distances:
STEP|93|Develop the medium-distance associations — they're specific enough to visualize but unexpected enough to be interesting
